    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36.45"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">45</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">KLIK</hi> <hi rend="italics">Radio 950, Inc. 
                        <lb/>
                    Covering Missouri from the State Capital with</hi> 5000 <hi rend="italics">Watts</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    <hi rend="caps">P.O. BOX 414 JEFFERSON CITY, MISSOURI</hi> 65101 <hi rend="italics">314 635-4136</hi> 
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>May 11, 1972</dateline> 
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Doctor John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>Skyrim Farm</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Doctor Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>About a month ago I received a letter from Mrs. Young saying you would be in Columbia by now, and I would like to arrange for the taping of the radio program as soon as possible.</p>
                
                <p>My calendar is pretty open and, as I have mentioned before, I could arrange the taping anytime convenient to you.</p>
                
                <p>We had also mentioned bringing our church youth group to Skyrim to visit the prayer garden and hear your stories of Black Elk. With the school year winding down and the kids about to scatter to vacations, jobs, and so forth, I'd like to bring them to Columbia on Sunday, the 21st, if it is agreeable to you. If not, perhaps we could work out a more convenient date in that same area. Our group usually meets here at 5:30, immediately after choir practice. That means we wouldn't reach your farm until about 6 o'clock or slightly afterwards. We could set the time up to early afternoon if you prefer.</p> 
                
                <p>You and Mrs. Thompson might want to telephone me about it. The number at the station is 635-4136.</p>
                
                <p>Mrs. Young was kind enough to send me a packet of items about you. I had heard of your new album of readings and had wanted it but did not know how to get it. It shall soon join your other two recordings on my shelf.</p>
                
                <p>Sometimes during our recording sessions, I plan to ask a sizeable favor of you. For 10 years I have been wondering how to pronounce your middle name.</p>
                
                <p>I have seen the paperback edition of <hi rend="underline">Black Elk Speaks</hi> on local bookshelves and the lady who runs the local magazine and the book shop says they are popular. I haven't bought one. I already have an older, dog-eared copy which is out on loan to another member of our staff who is just now discovering Neihardt.</p> 
               
                <p>We hope to hear from you soon about the visit and the program.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely,</salute>
                
                KLIK Radio 950, Inc. 
                    <signed>Bob Priddy</signed> 
                Bob Priddy, News Director 
                
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
